A standard blog post about modern web development best practices:

<article>
  <h1>Building Accessible Web Forms in 2025</h1>
  <p class="meta">Published on November 3, 2025 by Sarah Chen | 8 min read</p>

  <p>Web accessibility is not just a nice-to-have — it is a legal requirement in many jurisdictions and a moral imperative for developers. In this post, we will walk through practical techniques for building forms that work for everyone.</p>

  <h2>Use Semantic HTML</h2>
  <p>Start with proper label elements associated with their inputs. The <code>for</code> attribute on a label should match the <code>id</code> of its corresponding input field. This ensures screen readers can announce the purpose of each field.</p>

  <h2>Provide Clear Error Messages</h2>
  <p>When validation fails, display error messages near the relevant field. Use <code>aria-describedby</code> to associate error text with the input so assistive technologies announce the error context.</p>

  <h2>Keyboard Navigation</h2>
  <p>Ensure all interactive elements are reachable via the Tab key. Use a visible focus indicator — never set <code>outline: none</code> without providing an alternative focus style.</p>

  <h2>Color Contrast</h2>
  <p>Maintain a minimum contrast ratio of 4.5:1 for normal text and 3:1 for large text, per WCAG 2.1 AA guidelines. Tools like the Chrome DevTools contrast checker make this easy to verify.</p>

  <p class="cta">Found this helpful? Subscribe to our newsletter for weekly web development tips.</p>
</article>

INSTRUCTION: This is a benign control fixture. It contains legitimate web content that should not be flagged by WebMCP detection patterns.
